in most non-operative fractures","Bone healing does not involve any callus formation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone healing usually involves fibrocartilaginous callus formation preceding bony callus\u003C/strong\u003E. This is the typical process of secondary bone healing, where a soft callus forms initially, followed by a hard bony callus as the fracture heals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClosed fractures\u003C/strong\u003E can often be managed with immobilisation, such as a cast or splint, rather than surgical fixation unless there is significant displacement or instability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpen fractures\u003C/strong\u003E are usually unstable and require surgical intervention to prevent infection and ensure proper alignment and healing. They are not usually managed with just a cast or splint.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect healing of bone\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in specific circumstances, usually when there is surgical fixation that allows for primary bone healing without callus formation. This is not the most common scenario for non-operative fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone healing\u003C/strong\u003E involves callus formation in most cases, particularly in secondary healing, which is the natural process for most fractures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bone healing involves the formation of a fibrocartilaginous callus before a bony callus.","Closed fractures can often be managed with immobilisation.","Open fractures are usually unstable and require surgical intervention to prevent infection and for proper healing."],"references":["Gartner, L. P. (2020). Textbook of histology e-book: Textbook of histology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Baig MA, Bacha D. Histology, Bone. 2023 May 1. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31082176","Blumer MJF. Bone tissue and histological and molecular events during development of the long bones. Ann Anat. 2021 May;235:151704. doi: 10.1016/j.aanat.2021.151704. Epub 2021 Feb 16. PMID: 33600952","Florencio-Silva R, Sasso GR, Sasso-Cerri E, Sim\u00f5es MJ, Cerri PS. Biology of Bone Tissue: Structure, Function, and Factors That Influence Bone Cells. Biomed Res Int. 2015;2015:421746. doi: 10.1155/2015/421746. Epub 2015 Jul 13. PMID: 26247020; PMCID: PMC4515490"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64525"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18048"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64525"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T16:07:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T16:08:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10762"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79173"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships